notes.text: The multiplicity of small German states achieved real unity only with the rise of Prussia and the formation of the German Empire in the mid 19th century. After being defeated in the First World War, Germany was taken over in the 1930s by the Nazi dictatorship, which led to a policy of expansionism and eventually to complete defeat in the Second World War. Germany was occupied for a time by the victorious Allies and was partitioned. The western part (including West Berlin), which was occupied by the US, Britain, and France, became the Federal Republic of Germany or West Germany, with its capital at Bonn. The eastern part, occupied by the Soviet Union, became the German Democratic Republic or East Germany, with its capital in East Berlin. West Germany emerged as a major European industrial power and was a founder member of the EEC while the East remained under Soviet domination. After the general collapse of communism in eastern Europe, East and West Germany reunited on 3 October 1990

definitions: pursuing an occupation or activity at a particular place or in a particular way

examples.text: the artist was active in the 1920s
tigers are active mainly at night
a politically active student body
sexually active teenagers

definitions: participating or engaged in a particular sphere or activity in a positive or spontaneous rather than a passive way

examples.text: she was an active member of the society
he had never been very active in the affairs of the institute
he enjoyed the active support of the government

definitions: (of a thing) working; operative

examples.text: the old watermill was active until 1960

definitions: (of an electric circuit) capable of modifying its state or characteristics automatically in response to input or feedback

examples.text: the receiver is continuously active whenever the vehicle ignition is switched on

definitions: (of a volcano) that is erupting or has erupted in historical times

examples.text: the volcano became active on 28 March last year
Etna is Europe's highest and most active volcano

definitions: (of a disease) in which the symptoms are manifest; not in remission or latent

examples.text: active colitis

definitions: having a chemical or biological effect on something

examples.text: active ingredients

definitions: denoting a voice of verbs in which the subject is typically the person or thing performing the action and which can take a direct object (e.g. she loved him as opposed to the passive form he was loved).
an active form of a verb.

etymologies: late Middle English (in the sense ‘be united physically’; rare before the 18th century): from Latin connectere, from con- ‘together’ + nectere ‘bind’

definitions: bring together or into contact so that a real or notional link is established

examples.text: the electrodes were connected to a recording device

definitions: join together so as to provide access and communication

examples.text: all the buildings are connected by underground passages
the motorway connects with major routes from all parts of the country

definitions: link to a power or water supply

examples.text: by 1892 most of the village had been connected to the mains

definitions: put (someone) into contact by phone

examples.text: I was quickly connected to the police

definitions: (of a train, bus, aircraft, etc.) be timed to arrive at its destination just before another train, bus, etc., departs so that passengers can transfer

examples.text: the bus connects with trains from Windermere station

shortDefinitions: arrive just before another train etc.

definitions: associate or relate (something) in some respect

examples.text: employees are rewarded with bonuses connected to their firm's performance
jobs connected with the environment

definitions: provide or have a link or relationship with

examples.text: there was no evidence to connect Jefferson with the theft
the desire for religious faith connects up with profound needs at the core of our existence

definitions: form a relationship or feel an affinity

examples.text: he can't connect with anyone any more

definitions: (of a blow) hit the intended target

examples.text: the blow connected and he felt a burst of pain

etymologies: Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French buquet ‘tub, pail’, perhaps from Old English būc ‘belly, pitcher’

definitions: a roughly cylindrical open container with a handle, made of metal or plastic and used to hold and carry liquids

examples.text: a bucket and spade
an ice bucket

definitions: the contents of a bucket or the amount it can contain

examples.text: she emptied a bucket of water over them

definitions: large quantities of something, especially liquid

examples.text: I wept buckets

definitions: a compartment on the outer edge of a waterwheel

examples.text: the Laxey wheel had 168 buckets, each holding 24 gallons

definitions: the scoop of a dredger or grain elevator

examples.text: as the chain turns the buckets bite into the canal bed and scoop out the mud

definitions: a scoop attached to the front of a loader, digger, or tractor.
a unit of data that can be transferred from a backing store in a single operation.
rain heavily

examples.text: it was still bucketing down

notes.text: "it buckets down", "it is bucketing down", etc.

definitions: (of a vehicle) move quickly and jerkily

examples.text: the car came bucketing out of a side road
